CUCURBIT YELLOW VINE DISEASE, ETIOLOGY - USA
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 29 Jun 2002
From: Timothy S Schubert <schubet@doacs.state.fl.us> [edited]

It is interesting to note that _Serratia marcescens_ (known to be
saprophytic, harmlessly epiphytic on, or endophytic in plants, used as a
plant disease biocontrol agent, sometimes even pathogenic on humans and
insects) has recently been implicated in a new / emerging plant disease,
cucurbit yellow vine disease. [Plant Disease 2001; 85: 1031, Phytopathology
2000; 90: S63].
In this disease, the bacterial pathogen resides in the plant's phloem, a
rather unusual place for phytopathogenic bacteria to lodge. For some time
after this disease was first described in Texas and Oklahoma in 1988, the
pathogen was thought to be a fastidious phloem-inhabiting bacterium related
to the citrus greening pathogen in the genus _Liberobacter_, which is
transmitted by the citrus psyllid _Diaphorina citri_.
Phloem-feeding insect vectors are suspected of being involved in cucurbit
yellow vine pathogen dispersal, but to my knowledge, no vector has been
proven to date.
--
Tim Schubert
Florida Department of Agriculture & Consumer Services
Division of Plant Industry
Plant Pathology Section
PO Box 147100
Gainesville, FL 32614-7100
